<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="repeated-dosing-opening">
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The model in Part 1 describes what happens after treatment stops. But
        before treatment stops, medication is usually taken on a schedule. A
        simple way to model repeated dosing is to update the concentration at
        regular time intervals.
      </p>

      <p>
        Suppose a dose is taken every <m>T</m> days. Between doses, the medication
        concentration decays exponentially. If the elimination constant is
        <m>k</m>, then after <m>T</m> days, the concentration is multiplied by
      </p>

      <me>a = e^{-kT}.</me>

      <p>
        Then a new dose increases the concentration by an amount <m>D</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>H_n</m> be the medication concentration immediately after the
        <m>n</m>th dose.
      </p>

      <p>
        Explain why the concentration immediately after the next dose satisfies
      </p>

      <me>H_{n+1} = aH_n + D.</me>

      <p>
        In this model, what does each term represent?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose the half-life is <m>8</m> days and a dose is taken every
        <m>7</m> days.
      </p>

      <p>
        First compute
      </p>

      <me>k = \frac{\ln 2}{8}</me>

      <p>
        and then compute
      </p>

      <me>a = e^{-7k}.</me>

      <p>
        Interpret the number <m>a</m> in words.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For simplicity, suppose <m>D=1</m> and <m>H_0=1</m>. Use the recurrence
      </p>

      <me>H_{n+1}=aH_n+1</me>

      <p>
        to compute <m>H_1,H_2,H_3,H_4</m>. Round your answers to three decimal
        places.
      </p>

      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell><m>n</m></cell>
          <cell><m>H_n</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>0</m></cell>
          <cell><m>1</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>1</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>2</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>3</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>4</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <em>steady state</em> for the recurrence
      </p>

      <me>H_{n+1}=aH_n+D</me>

      <p>
        is a value <m>H^\ast</m> such that if <m>H_n=H^\ast</m>, then
        <m>H_{n+1}=H^\ast</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Find a formula for <m>H^\ast</m> in terms of <m>a</m> and <m>D</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The recurrence
      </p>

      <me>H_{n+1}=aH_n+D</me>

      <p>
        is not a linear transformation because of the added constant <m>D</m>.
        However, it can be written as a matrix update by adding an extra
        coordinate:
      </p>

      <me>
        \begin{pmatrix}
        H_{n+1}\\
        1
        \end{pmatrix}
        =
        \begin{pmatrix}
        a &amp; D\\
        0 &amp; 1
        \end{pmatrix}
        \begin{pmatrix}
        H_n\\
        1
        \end{pmatrix}.
      </me>

      <p>
        Verify that this matrix equation gives the same recurrence.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In this model, regular dosing does not simply keep the concentration
        constant. Instead, the concentration moves toward a steady pattern
        determined by the dose size, dosing interval, and half-life.
      </p>

      <p>
        Explain why this matters when thinking about interruptions to medication
        access. What information would be missing if we only knew whether someone
        had taken a dose recently?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
</worksheet>